:"1560","about 1483":"omkring 1483","Therfield, Hertfordshire, England":"Therfield, Hertfordshire, England","of Therfield,Hertfordshire,England":"Therfield, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1483–":"circa 1483–Overleden","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1525–1573":"1525–1573","1483–Female":"1483–Overleden","1525":"1525","before 1524":"vóór 1524","1500":"1500","1573":"1573","1483":"1483","1560":"1560","about 1483":"circa 1483","Therfield, Hertfordshire, England":"Therfield, Hertfordshire, England","of Therfield,Hertfordshire,England":"Therfield, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1483–":"about 1483–Deceased","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1525–1573":"1525–1573","1483–Female":"1483–Deceased","1525":"1525","before 1524":"before 1524","1500":"1500","1573":"1573","1483":"1483","1560":"1560","about 1483":"about 1483","Therfield, Hertfordshire, England":"Therfield, Hertfordshire, England","of Therfield,Hertfordshire,England":"Therfield, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ingold","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Ingle  .","Swiss German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ingwald</i>, formed with <i>Ing-</i> (see   Ingle   1) + <i>walt(an)</i> ‘to rule’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ingle","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ingel</i>, <i>Ingald</i>, <i>Ingold</i> (Old Norse <i>Ingialdr</i>, <i>Ingœld</i>, itself apparently borrowed from the Old English <i>Ingeld</i>, a name of ancient Germanic origin consisting of an intensive prefix <i>in-</i> + <i>geld-</i> ‘reward, forfeit’).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ingulf</i>, representing either Old Norse <i>Ingólfr</i>, <i>Ingulf</i> or its ancient Germanic cognate, <i>Ingenwulf</i>, introduced to England by the Normans; the first element is derived from an ancient Germanic heroic name, and the second is ‘wolf’. As a surname it either died out or was absorbed by <i>Ingle</i> and its variants.","Americanized form of German <b>Ingel</b>: from a short form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names formed with <i>Ing-</i> (see 1 above). The surname <i>Ingel</i> is very rare in Germany."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Rose Ingold was born about 1483, in Therfield, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Smythe before 1524. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1483–":"umbes 1483–Surnud","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1525–1573":"1525–1573","1483–Female":"1483–Surnud","1525":"1525","before 1524":"enne 1524","1500":"1500","1573":"1573","1483":"1483","1560":"1560","about 1483":"umbes 1483","Therfield, Her